description:
The internal compiler errors (ICEs) of the Intel ifx compiler (<=2024.2.1) disappear if two OpenMP clauses are excluded. Properly matching OpenMP END clauses seem to help, too.
@hfp Maybe, that helps the ifx compiler developers.
Unfortunately, the CP2K icx/ifx binary still shows runtime errors in dbcsr_mm.F:588.

@marci73 I hope it was ok to make a suggestion for the text on this page: 

https://manual.cp2k.org/trunk/methods/properties/optical/index.html

Comments & additions are always welcome, of course.

PR #3177 removed some Spack files used by some of the Docker containers. This PR removes such containers and the generating code.

@mtaillefumier, can you please have a look if this is OK?

The next steps would be to add environments replacing the CUDA and ROCm Dockerfiles.

Fixes #2485 .
Fixes #2488 .

@recohen Can you double-check?

This adds a generic Fortran wrapper for PyTorch's [C++ API](https://pytorch.org/cppdocs/).

An alternative would have been to use [pytorch-fortran](https://github.com/alexeedm/pytorch-fortran), but it currently does not support dictionaries and it pulls in a full Python interpreter via [pybind11](https://github.com/alexeedm/pytorch-fortran/blob/57744bd353ed485be6329c652e95b529443148d1/src/proxy_lib/torch_proxy.cpp#L29).

@gabriele16, the `nequip_unittest.F` should be equivalent to [your example](https://github.com/gabriele16/nequip-C-fortran-interface/blob/main/nequip_interface/fortran_call.f90). I also took the liberty of including your [water model](https://github.com/gabriele16/nequip-C-fortran-interface/blob/main/nequip_interface/water-deploy.pth). I hope this is ok?

Fixes #2103 and #1936.

Turns out the solution was `export I_MPI_FABRICS='shm'`.

@hfp, is this worth a bug report?

@pcazade, please take a look at this PR. It fixes an issue that our [farming test](https://dashboard.cp2k.org/archive/farming/index.html) found. The problem is that the space group output gets written to [default_output_unit](https://github.com/cp2k/cp2k/blob/master/src/motion/space_groups_types.F#L131) instead of using a [printkey](https://www.cp2k.org/dev:printkey). 

In this PR I'm changing the output to the exiting [PROGRAM_RUN_INFO](https://manual.cp2k.org/trunk/CP2K_INPUT/MOTION/GEO_OPT/PRINT/PROGRAM_RUN_INFO.html) and [STRESS](https://manual.cp2k.org/trunk/CP2K_INPUT/MOTION/PRINT/STRESS.html) printkeys. Furthermore, I'm removing the `SPGR_FILE_NAME` keyword and renaming `SPGR_PRINT_LEVEL` into `SPGR_PRINT_ATOMS`.

The output of [PROGRAM_RUN_INFO](https://manual.cp2k.org/trunk/CP2K_INPUT/MOTION/GEO_OPT/PRINT/PROGRAM_RUN_INFO.html) can still be redirected to a file. Please let me know if this works for you or if I should rather create a separate printkey?

As preparation for #1072 I've converted the comments in our C code to match [Doxygen's preference](https://www.doxygen.nl/manual/docblocks.html) using the following script:

```python
#!/usr/bin/python3

import os

def main():
    for root, dirs, files in os.walk("./src"):
        for fn in files:
            abs_fn = os.path.join(root, fn)
            ext = fn.rsplit(".", 1)[-1]
            if ext not in ("h", "c", "cu"):
                continue
            print("Working on: " + abs_fn)

            old_lines = open(abs_fn).read().split("\n")
            box_open = False
            new_lines = []
            for line in old_lines:
                if not box_open and line.startswith("//********"):
                    new_lines.append("/" + ("*" * 79))
                    box_open = True
                elif box_open and line.startswith("//********"):
                    new_lines.append(" " + ("*" * 78) + "/")
                    box_open = False
                elif box_open:
                    assert line.startswith("//")
                    new_lines.append(" *" + line[2:])
                else:
                    new_lines.append(line)

            assert not box_open
            open(abs_fn, "w").write("\n".join(new_lines))

main()
```

In this PR, LIBXSMM is used to accelerate the contraction of 3-center integrals from pgf to sgf. The present code together with #869 allows for a cost reduction of 30% to 50% on the 3-center integrals calculation in XAS_TDP (depending on the simulated system and machine used).

@pseewald If you think that this can be useful for your tensor code and/or other methods using 3-center integrals, let me know and I can make the changes there too.

@hfp I stopped short of writing a version dependent code and simply check for the -D__LIBXSMM flag with a fallback on BLAS. I tested the code with versions 1.9.0 and the current development branch, assuming everything in between would work.

  * bug fix in print_coeffs();

  * add an option to print MOs in spherical Gaussians. This is now the default
    option, as g-orbitals printed in MOLDEN format using Cartesian Gaussians
    do not look identical to the same orbitals printed as cube files;

  * consistent names of input sections:

    ** DFT/SCF/PRINT/MOS_MOLDEN has been renamed to DFT/PRINT/MO_MOLDEN in
       order to be consistetnt with DFT/PRINT/MO_CUBE;

    ** DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MOS_MOLDEN has been renamed to
       DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MINBAS_MOLDEN in order to be consistent
       with DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MINBAS_COBE.

  * bug fix in print_coeffs();

  * add an option to print MOs in spherical Gaussians. This is now the default
    option, as g-orbitals printed in MOLDEN format using Cartesian Gaussians
    do not look identical to the same orbitals printed as cube files;

  * consistent names of input sections:

    ** DFT/SCF/PRINT/MOS_MOLDEN has been renamed to DFT/PRINT/MO_MOLDEN in
       order to be consistetnt with DFT/PRINT/MO_CUBE;

    ** DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MOS_MOLDEN has been renamed to
       DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MINBAS_MOLDEN in order to be consistent
       with DFT/PRINT/MINBAS_ANALYSIS/MINBAS_COBE.

* replace $nprocs with $NPROCS in install_openblas.sh;
* enable C++ MPI binding in install_openmpi.sh.

C++ binding is only needed to compile CP2K with PLUMED. However linking flags "-lmpi_cxx -lstdc++" appear in generated local arch files even if we do not use PLUMED at all.
